      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":9,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy (walk/run as needed)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first phase is all about rebuilding tissue tolerance in your foot and re-establishing the habit of consistent movement — three days per week, capped at 20 minutes per run, exactly as your physio has cleared you. Every run stays at the easy end of your pace range (5:58/km), and you should treat any foot pain as a signal to shift to walk/run immediately. A deload week occurs in week 4, dropping volume by roughly 20% to let your body consolidate the adaptation. No heroics here — the goal is to finish every run feeling like you could have done more. That restraint is the work.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":12,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":351,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":344,\"notes\":\"If your physio has cleared you for longer efforts by this point, you can begin gently extending your Saturday long run beyond 20 minutes — but only with explicit clearance. Until then, the volume increase comes from adding a third run day more consistently and letting the 20-minute runs accumulate. Cross-training (cycling, pool running, swimming) is a great option here if you want more aerobic stimulus without foot loading. Week 8 is a deload week. This phase is about proving to your foot that running is safe — consistency over intensity, every time.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":26,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% moderate\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":324,\"notes\":\"This phase assumes you have received clearance to extend run duration and that your foot has been pain-free for at least two consecutive weeks. The Saturday long run begins to take shape as a genuine long run — building toward 60–70 minutes at easy effort. Volume increases no more than 10% week over week. Week 12 is a deload. Tempo and interval work remain off the table until you have explicit speed clearance from your physio — your VDOT of 46.5 tells us the fitness is in there, and it will come back faster than you expect once the foundation is solid. Patience here pays dividends later.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":26,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":32,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":338,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"This phase is conditional — it only begins if your physio has cleared you for speed work and your foot has been fully symptom-free. If that clearance hasn't come, simply extend the Build phase and treat this as continued base building. If you are cleared, tempo efforts (at 4:29/km) can be introduced cautiously — starting with short 5–8 minute tempo segments within an easy run, not standalone hard sessions. The long run continues to grow. This is where your pre-injury fitness starts to resurface, and it can feel exciting. Channel that energy into consistency, not acceleration.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"A final recovery week to close out the 16-week plan. Easy running only, no pressure, no targets. This is a moment to reflect on how far you have come — from 2.5 km run/walk sessions to a rebuilt aerobic base. Use this week to assess how your foot feels, reconnect with your physio for a progress check, and think about what your next goal looks like. You have done the hard, unglamorous work of coming back carefully. That is something to be genuinely proud of.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James, your training history shows real discipline — you have been running consistently at 5:58/km, respecting the 20-minute cap, and listening to your foot. That is exactly the right approach, and this plan is built to honour that. Your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 (from a 44:00 10K) tells us your aerobic engine is strong. The challenge right now is not fitness — it is tissue tolerance. Plantar fasciitis responds well to gradual, consistent loading, and poorly to sudden spikes in volume or intensity. So this 16-week plan is structured around three principles: (1) Never exceed 10% weekly volume increase. (2) Deload every 3–4 weeks to let connective tissue adapt. (3) No speed work until your physio explicitly clears it — your threshold pace of 4:29/km and interval pace of 4:12/km will be there waiting for you when the time is right. The plan is also deliberately conservative in the early phases because returning from plantar fasciitis is non-linear. Some weeks your foot will feel great; others it will talk back. The walk/run protocol is not a fallback — it is a legitimate training tool, and using it when you need it is smart coaching, not failure. Three days per week with a Saturday long run is a perfectly sound structure for this return. Consistency across weeks matters far more than any single session.\",\"warnings\":\"This plan is built around your physiotherapist's current clearance: easy running only, maximum 20 minutes per run, walk/run if any foot pain is present, and no speed work until cleared. You must not begin Phase 3 (Build) or beyond without explicit physio clearance to extend duration, and you must not begin any tempo or interval work without explicit speed clearance. If you experience a return of foot pain — especially sharp heel pain in the morning or after sitting — stop running and contact your physio before your next session. Do not redistribute missed mileage to other days if you miss a run. If you miss a week, simply resume where you left off. This plan is a guide, not a contract. Your foot's feedback is always the most important data point.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
